/**
  @page gallery Gallery
  @brief A visual showcase of simulations and results produced with Rodin

  @m_keywords{Gallery, Showcase, Visualization, Results, Examples}

  @tableofcontents

  @m_footernavigation

  @section gallery-intro Overview

  This gallery showcases results from simulations built with the Rodin
  framework. Each entry links to the corresponding example or tutorial page
  where you can find the full source code and step-by-step explanations.

  @section gallery-pdes Partial Differential Equations

  @subsection gallery-pdes-poisson Poisson Equation

  @image html PDEs/Poisson.png width=360px

  The @ref examples-pdes-poisson "Poisson equation" example solves the
  classic scalar PDE @f$ -\Delta u = f @f$ on the unit square with
  homogeneous Dirichlet boundary conditions, using
  @ref Rodin::Variational::P1 "P1" finite elements and the
  @ref Rodin::Solver::CG "CG" solver.

  @subsection gallery-pdes-elasticity Linear Elasticity

  @image html Elasticity.png width=360px

  The @ref examples-pdes-elasticity "elasticity" example solves the
  linearized elasticity system @f$ -\nabla \cdot \sigma(u) = 0 @f$
  with mixed Dirichlet/Neumann boundary conditions. It demonstrates
  vector-valued @ref Rodin::Variational::P1 "P1" spaces and the
  `LinearElasticityIntegral` bilinear form.

  @subsection gallery-pdes-helmholtz Helmholtz Equation

  @image html PDEs/Helmholtz_placeholder.png width=360px

  The @ref examples-pdes-helmholtz "Helmholtz equation" example solves
  the complex-valued PDE @f$ -\Delta u - k^2 u = f @f$ using
  @ref Rodin::Variational::P1 "P1<Complex>" finite element spaces.
  This demonstrates Rodin's support for complex-valued computations.

  @subsection gallery-pdes-navierstokes Navier–Stokes Equations

  @image html PDEs/NavierStokes_placeholder.png width=360px

  The @ref examples-pdes-navierstokes "Navier–Stokes" tutorial covers the
  steady incompressible Navier–Stokes equations using Taylor–Hood elements
  (@ref Rodin::Variational::H1 "H1" order 2 for velocity, order 1 for
  pressure) with Picard iteration.

  @subsection gallery-pdes-periodic Periodic Poisson Equation

  The @ref examples-pdes-periodic "periodic Poisson" example demonstrates
  how to impose periodic boundary conditions using `PeriodicBC` and a DOF
  correspondence map. The solution on opposite edges of the domain is
  constrained to be equal, simulating a tiling pattern.

  @subsection gallery-pdes-surface Reaction-Diffusion on a Surface

  The @ref examples-pdes-surfacemesh "surface mesh" example solves a
  reaction-diffusion equation @f$ -\Delta_\Gamma u + u = f @f$ on a
  curved 3D manifold. It demonstrates that Rodin handles surface PDEs
  transparently — the same `Integral(Grad(u), Grad(v))` syntax
  automatically computes the surface gradient.

  @section gallery-optimization Optimization

  @subsection gallery-shapeopt-cantilever Shape Optimization: Cantilever

  @image html SimpleCantilever.png width=360px

  The @ref examples-shapeoptimization-simple_cantilever "simple cantilever"
  example performs boundary-variation shape optimization of a cantilever
  beam, minimizing the compliance (structural stiffness) subject to a
  volume constraint. The shape gradient is computed and regularized via the
  Hilbert extension-regularization procedure, and the mesh is updated using
  the @ref Rodin::External::MMG "MMG" remesher.

  @subsection gallery-shapeopt-levelset Level-Set Shape Optimization

  @image html LevelSetCantilever.png width=360px

  The @ref examples-shapeoptimization-levelset_cantilever "level-set
  cantilever" example combines body-fitted meshing with level-set
  techniques. The optimizer advects a signed-distance function and recovers
  the implicit domain at each iteration using the
  @ref Rodin::External::MMG "MMG" level-set discretizer.

  @subsection gallery-density-temp Density Optimization: Temperature

  @image html SIMPTemperatureMinimization.png width=360px

  The @ref examples-density_optimization-simp_temperature_minimization
  "temperature minimization" example uses the SIMP (Solid Isotropic
  Material with Penalization) approach to find an optimal material
  distribution that minimizes the average temperature in a domain.

  @section gallery-geometry Mesh Geometry and Utilities

  Rodin provides a rich set of geometric operations for creating,
  transforming, and querying meshes:

  - **UniformGrid**: Generate structured meshes of triangles, quads,
    tetrahedra, hexahedra, or wedges in any dimension. See
    @ref examples-geometry-uniformgrid "UniformGrid example".
  - **Scale and displace**: Transform mesh coordinates with
    `mesh.scale()` and `mesh.displace()`.
  - **Trim**: Remove cells by attribute to extract subdomains.
  - **Skin**: Extract the boundary surface of a volumetric mesh.
  - **CCL**: Connected component labeling for domain decomposition.
  - **Connectivity**: Compute topological incidence relations between
    mesh entities of any dimension. See
    @ref examples-geometry-connectivity "Connectivity example".

  @section gallery-io Visualization and I/O

  Rodin supports exporting simulation data in the
  @ref Rodin::IO::XDMF "XDMF" format, which can be opened directly in
  [ParaView](https://www.paraview.org/) for advanced 3D visualization
  including time-series animation, vector glyphs, and surface warping.

  See the @ref examples-io-xdmf "XDMF example" for a complete guide.

  The supported mesh file formats are:
  - **MFEM** (`IO::FileFormat::MFEM`): Text-based, used by the MFEM library
  - **MEDIT** (`IO::FileFormat::MEDIT`): Native for MMG/INRIA tools
  - **HDF5** (`IO::FileFormat::HDF5`): Binary, for large-scale simulations

  @section gallery-see-also See Also

  - @ref examples-index "Examples and tutorials"
  - @ref guides-io "I/O in Rodin"
  - @ref guides-weak-formulations "Weak formulations"
  - @ref notation-index "Notation reference"

  */
